    "summary": "The proto-Badarian phase refers to the earliest precursors of the Badarian culture, one of the oldest Predynastic cultures of Upper Egypt, whose earliest manifestations date to around 6500–6000 BCE in the region around modern Qena and Asyut. The Badarian people combined herding, hunting, and limited cultivation in a Nile Valley environment and produced some of the finest thin-walled, rippled pottery of the ancient world.\n\nBadarian burials reflect an early sense of social differentiation, with grave goods including pottery, ivory combs, and jewelry suggesting that status distinctions were beginning to emerge in Nile Valley societies. The culture is also notable for evidence of copper working, making it one of the earliest contexts for metal use in northeastern Africa. The Badarian tradition laid cultural and social foundations that the later [[event:1497|Badarian]] and Naqada cultures would build upon on the path toward Egyptian civilization.",
